00:12:12,802 --> 00:12:14,363
and figure out what to do with it later.

247
00:12:14,363 --> 00:12:17,263
Don't try to justify why things are the way they are.

248
00:12:17,978 --> 00:12:18,479
take it all in.

249
00:12:18,479 --> 00:12:21,041
Attention span.

250
00:12:21,041 --> 00:12:23,403
Now, if you were working on a game like 10 years ago,

251
00:12:23,403 --> 00:12:25,064
you could probably assume that the player will

252
00:12:25,064 --> 00:12:26,525
spend some time with it.

253
00:12:26,525 --> 00:12:30,168
But nowadays, if your tutorial annoys the player,

254
00:12:30,168 --> 00:12:32,169
he'll just close the game and move to the other one

255
00:12:32,169 --> 00:12:35,011
because there are so many games nowadays,

256
00:12:35,011 --> 00:12:37,854
and it's so easy to get distracted.

257
00:12:37,854 --> 00:12:40,355
So even the first few minutes of the game

258
00:12:40,355 --> 00:12:41,656
have to be very, very engaging.

259
00:12:42,012 --> 00:12:44,954
For example, I come from a browser games background,

260
00:12:44,954 --> 00:12:46,375
from Flash games background,

261
00:12:46,375 --> 00:12:48,556
and this is one game that I worked on

262
00:12:48,556 --> 00:12:51,038
in which you control two characters at the same time.

263
00:12:51,500 --> 00:12:54,060
the small character with WASD and the big character

264
00:12:54,060 --> 00:12:56,601
by clicking on the screen to move him.

265
00:12:56,601 --> 00:12:58,922
And I tried so many ways to teach the players this

266
00:12:58,922 --> 00:13:00,902
and nothing worked, nobody understood it.

267
00:13:00,902 --> 00:13:03,383
And then I kind of gave up and I did this,

268
00:13:03,383 --> 00:13:07,484
which I'm not really proud of, but hey, it works.

269
00:13:07,484 --> 00:13:10,065
And yes, in Flash games, even if the loading screen

270
00:13:10,065 --> 00:13:12,746
is bothering the player, they'll just close the tab.

271
00:13:12,746 --> 00:13:15,267
So another thing to keep in mind, game literacy.

272
00:13:15,267 --> 00:13:18,788
This is the assumption you make as a developer.

273
00:13:19,414 --> 00:13:22,135
of how much the player knows about games in general.

274
00:13:22,135 --> 00:13:24,036
So for example, you can assume that the player

275
00:13:24,036 --> 00:13:26,637
doesn't know anything, and you have to teach them

276
00:13:26,637 --> 00:13:29,098
everything from looking around with the mouse

277
00:13:29,098 --> 00:13:33,480
or moving around with WASD, which is what Overwatch does.

278
00:13:33,480 --> 00:13:36,782
Or you can be like Pledis Inside,

279
00:13:36,782 --> 00:13:38,923
where they assume you know everything

280
00:13:38,923 --> 00:13:40,124
and they don't tell you anything.

281
00:13:40,124 --> 00:13:42,105
This is the first thing you see when you open the game.

282
00:13:42,657 --> 00:13:45,941
and you have to figure out that you move with the joystick.

283
00:13:45,941 --> 00:13:47,123
They don't tell you anything.

284
00:13:47,123 --> 00:13:49,806
There are no prompts on the screen.

285
00:13:49,806 --> 00:13:52,930
And in my point of view, this makes the game better.

286
00:13:52,930 --> 00:13:55,273
For example, in here, they could easily tell you,

287
00:13:55,273 --> 00:13:57,475
press A to jump, but they don't do that.

288
00:13:57,475 --> 00:13:59,498
They allow you to figure it out on your own,

289
00:13:59,498 --> 00:14:01,861
and it makes the game more moody.

290
00:14:01,861 --> 00:14:02,521
It's better.

291
00:14:03,595 --> 00:14:04,676
because it benefits the game.

292
00:14:04,676 --> 00:14:07,639
There's also the option of no tutorials.

293
00:14:07,639 --> 00:14:10,041
Now, it's not written in stone

294
00:14:10,041 --> 00:14:12,424
that all games need to have a tutorial.

295
00:14:12,424 --> 00:14:13,865
For example, Starseed Pilgrim,

296
00:14:13,865 --> 00:14:15,627
it's a game where it doesn't tell you

297
00:14:15,627 --> 00:14:17,149
what to do on purpose.

298
00:14:17,149 --> 00:14:18,050
It's about mystery.

299
00:14:18,050 --> 00:14:21,053
It's about figuring out how the game works,

300
00:14:21,053 --> 00:14:22,995
and the game is better because of this.

301
00:14:23,876 --> 00:14:25,537
Also, Pokemon Go.

302
00:14:25,537 --> 00:14:28,759
Now, let's not discuss if it's finished or not,

303
00:14:28,759 --> 00:14:29,620
because it's not even 1.0 yet,

304
00:14:29,620 --> 00:14:32,622
but the thing is, for example,

305
00:14:32,622 --> 00:14:34,723
I didn't know that I can spin the ball

306
00:14:34,723 --> 00:14:36,524
or how the Pokemon tracker worked.

307
00:14:36,524 --> 00:14:38,285
And these are things that I found out

308
00:14:38,285 --> 00:14:40,347
from other players in the real world

309
00:14:40,347 --> 00:14:42,768
that came up to me and explained these mechanics to me.

310
00:14:43,297 --> 00:14:45,539
And that made the game better for me.

311
00:14:45,539 --> 00:14:48,381
It encouraged the social aspect of the game.

312
00:14:48,381 --> 00:14:51,144
And then I explained those things to other players.

313
00:14:51,144 --> 00:14:53,927
So regardless if they designed it like that or not,

314
00:14:53,927 --> 00:14:56,509
it made the game better from my point of view.

315
00:14:58,584 --> 00:15:04,471
So, in case you have like very weird mechanics, you can still make things easy to understand

316
00:15:04,471 --> 00:15:06,593
without simplifying your mechanics.

317
00:15:06,593 --> 00:15:08,595
And you do this by using standards.

318
00:15:08,595 --> 00:15:13,241
Now, we all know green is good, red is bad.

319
00:15:13,241 --> 00:15:15,002
We all know that lava is bad.

320
00:15:15,002 --> 00:15:17,005
You don't have to tell the player to avoid it.

321
00:15:17,005 --> 00:15:18,306
It's very instinctive.

322
00:15:19,267 --> 00:15:22,851
In case you're making an interface,

323
00:15:22,851 --> 00:15:25,695
red is usually used for health, blue is for mana.

324
00:15:25,695 --> 00:15:27,817
Some developers use green for health

325
00:15:27,817 --> 00:15:28,758
and blue is still mana,

326
00:15:28,758 --> 00:15:30,860
unless you're making an anime fighter,

327
00:15:30,860 --> 00:15:32,662
in which case you just use all the colors there are.

328
00:15:33,522 --> 00:15:34,462
Or Spider-Man.

329
00:15:34,462 --> 00:15:37,402
But yeah, anyway, we take this for granted.

330
00:15:37,402 --> 00:15:39,583
And the player already knows that red is bad.

331
00:15:39,583 --> 00:15:43,764
And you can even take these standards

332
00:15:43,764 --> 00:15:47,364
and flip them on their head to make fun of the player

333
00:15:47,364 --> 00:15:49,125
if your game allows you to do that.

334
00:15:49,125 --> 00:15:50,665
And it makes the experience better.

335
00:15:50,665 --> 00:15:53,145
Other cool things.

336
00:15:53,145 --> 00:15:55,126
Key standards.

337
00:15:55,126 --> 00:15:57,266
Now, we all know that in a shooter, for example,

338
00:15:57,266 --> 00:15:58,387
you move with double ESD.

339
00:15:59,368 --> 00:16:02,450
E is the use key, F is flashlight,

340
00:16:02,450 --> 00:16:07,275
control is crouch, and yes,

341
00:16:07,275 --> 00:16:09,537
unlike colors, please don't change this.

342
00:16:09,537 --> 00:16:11,558
Please keep these standards,

343
00:16:11,558 --> 00:16:14,441
because otherwise you will end up with something like this,

344
00:16:14,441 --> 00:16:17,844
which you don't want to do because it's very weird.

345
00:16:17,844 --> 00:16:23,149
So yeah, you can use all these to make your games

346
00:16:23,149 --> 00:16:25,350
more engaging, basically.

347
00:16:27,394 --> 00:16:28,174
Directing attention.

348
00:16:28,174 --> 00:16:31,536
Now, tutorials aren't only about teaching mechanics.

349
00:16:31,536 --> 00:16:34,437
They're also about navigating a space,

350
00:16:34,437 --> 00:16:37,778
or basically directing where the player will go next.

351
00:16:37,778 --> 00:16:40,379
And for that, we can use things like contrast.

352
00:16:40,379 --> 00:16:43,160
All the games use this, and it's super, super effective

353
00:16:43,160 --> 00:16:44,381
because it's very subtle.

354
00:16:44,381 --> 00:16:48,703
It's not like an arrow pointing where you have to go.

355
00:16:48,703 --> 00:16:50,343
For example, in this screenshot,

356
00:16:50,343 --> 00:16:52,124
you already know where you're gonna go next

357
00:16:52,124 --> 00:16:53,484
strictly because of the lighting.

358
00:16:53,484 --> 00:16:56,906
Other games do it more directly by using cables.

359
00:16:58,345 --> 00:17:01,465
For example, in The Witness, you solve digital puzzles

360
00:17:01,465 --> 00:17:02,626
and they're connected by cables.

361
00:17:02,626 --> 00:17:05,186
And once you solve one, the cable lights up,

362
00:17:05,186 --> 00:17:07,327
leading you to the next puzzle.

363
00:17:07,327 --> 00:17:09,927
So if your game allows, Portal does the same thing,

364
00:17:09,927 --> 00:17:13,028
you should do this because it's a more direct way

365
00:17:13,028 --> 00:17:17,249
to tell the player where to go.

366
00:17:17,249 --> 00:17:19,309
Other games are like super blunt about it

367
00:17:19,309 --> 00:17:21,069
and they just have a magical flying orb

368
00:17:21,069 --> 00:17:22,230
telling you where to go.

369
00:17:23,574 --> 00:17:24,594
So yeah, other things.

370
00:17:24,594 --> 00:17:25,355
Localization.

371
00:17:25,355 --> 00:17:28,016
Now I'm not talking about translating your game,

372
00:17:28,016 --> 00:17:30,917
but we've all played PlayStation games.

373
00:17:30,917 --> 00:17:34,198
We all know that X is confirm and circle is back.

374
00:17:34,198 --> 00:17:36,239
But have you ever played a Japanese game

375
00:17:36,239 --> 00:17:39,140
and figured out that they're flipped around

376
00:17:39,140 --> 00:17:42,461
and you were very confused for a few minutes like I was?

377
00:17:42,461 --> 00:17:46,003
So yes, things might be the same everywhere.

378
00:17:46,003 --> 00:17:48,464
So keep in mind where your game will be played.

379
00:17:49,387 --> 00:17:52,768
take all these things into consideration.

380
00:17:52,768 --> 00:17:56,409
Controllers are another very interesting thing

381
00:17:56,409 --> 00:17:57,549
to make your game more intuitive.

382
00:17:57,549 --> 00:17:59,289
For example, a trigger on a controller

383
00:17:59,289 --> 00:18:01,210
feels like pulling a trigger on a gun

384
00:18:01,210 --> 00:18:02,730
or like accelerating a vehicle.

385
00:18:02,730 --> 00:18:06,351
The Wiimote is designed to be used as a sword,

386
00:18:06,351 --> 00:18:08,852
and many games take advantage of that.

387
00:18:09,687 --> 00:18:13,909
And VR controllers, they open up so many possibilities.

388
00:18:13,909 --> 00:18:15,889
For example, this is something I really like

389
00:18:15,889 --> 00:18:17,530
from Hover Junkers.

390
00:18:17,530 --> 00:18:20,271
It's a game where you reload your revolver

391
00:18:20,271 --> 00:18:22,692
by pressing the trackpad.

392
00:18:22,692 --> 00:18:24,153
You rotate your thumb on the trackpad,

393
00:18:24,153 --> 00:18:25,173
so you put the bullets in,

394
00:18:25,173 --> 00:18:27,815
and you just slap the chamber back in,

395
00:18:27,815 --> 00:18:30,196
which is a very intuitive thing to do.

396
00:18:30,196 --> 00:18:31,676
You don't have to tell the player,

397
00:18:31,676 --> 00:18:33,237
press X to reload.

398
00:18:34,919 --> 00:18:37,422
For example, when I got the Oculus Touch controllers,

399
00:18:37,422 --> 00:18:40,465
the first time I got them, I looked at the thumbsticks

400
00:18:40,465 --> 00:18:43,449
and I noticed that the surface is shiny and I was like.

401
00:18:44,018 --> 00:18:45,599
That's horrible, who would do such a thing?

402
00:18:45,599 --> 00:18:47,959
But then I realized that they're actually

403
00:18:47,959 --> 00:18:51,900
capacitive surfaces that are also used on the triggers.

404
00:18:51,900 --> 00:18:54,701
And us developers can use those to figure out

405
00:18:54,701 --> 00:18:57,301
if the finger is touching that surface or not.

406
00:18:57,301 --> 00:18:59,822
And based on that alone, we can allow the player

407
00:18:59,822 --> 00:19:04,022
to do very intuitive gestures without pressing any button,

408
00:19:04,022 --> 00:19:05,623
just by moving their hands.

409
00:19:05,623 --> 00:19:08,383
So things like these are super exciting for the future

410
00:19:08,383 --> 00:19:12,244
and for designing more intuitive tutorials.

411
00:19:13,811 --> 00:19:19,014
And VR in general is super interesting because, for example, in Fruit Ninja, they don't have

412
00:19:19,014 --> 00:19:20,815
to teach you how to swing a sword.

413
00:19:20,815 --> 00:19:22,336
You already know how to do that.

414
00:19:22,336 --> 00:19:23,857
It's intuitive.

415
00:19:23,857 --> 00:19:28,320
In Space Pirate Trainer, they don't have to teach you how to avoid bullets.

416
00:19:28,733 --> 00:19:32,474
it's very intrinsic that when you see a projectile coming towards you,

417
00:19:32,474 --> 00:19:36,395
you lean in the other direction, and that's a mechanic of the game.

418
00:19:36,395 --> 00:19:39,717
And that's why it's so natural to interact with things in VR, because

419
00:19:39,717 --> 00:19:44,098
once you remap the hands in the virtual world, you just

420
00:19:44,098 --> 00:19:46,379
interact naturally with everything around you.

421
00:19:47,039 --> 00:19:50,422
For more traditional kind of text or buttons,

422
00:19:50,422 --> 00:19:52,744
they are usually mapped on the controller,

423
00:19:52,744 --> 00:19:55,146
so they follow your controller.

424
00:19:55,146 --> 00:19:56,667
And the interesting thing about VR

425
00:19:56,667 --> 00:19:58,989
is that in traditional games, you would usually

426
00:19:58,989 --> 00:20:02,311
tell the player the goal and how to get to the goal.

427
00:20:02,311 --> 00:20:04,553
Now, in VR, you don't necessarily have to do that.

